The ‘Bee Car’ That Avoids Collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was inspired, this time around, by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at the Nissan Advanced Technical Center Motor Co. have created this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C represents the development of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that looks a lot like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the eyes composed of the bee, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is known as a Laser Range Finder.
The latter detects the obstacles that are located over a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance up to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcating its 90-degree or higher wheels to avoid collision.
The biggest difference compared to any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is entirely instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Moving Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned upwards or downwards or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like the bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
" Every second this device should only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to keep the information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, which is why it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new collision-prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced into the series cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to its destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
