Morgan Stanley opens its capital at MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry into its round table of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan’s first bank, which will spend nine billion dollars to take 21% of its capital, a new one welcomed by a sharp drop in its stock market price.
A week after unveiling a tentative deal, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9 percent of Morgan Stanley’s common stock at a unit price of $25.25, or a total of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the acquisition of convertible securities with a return of 10% and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall operation would be carried out on the basis of an average unit price of $29, or 28% above its current price.
However, Morgan Stanley lost 6.79% to $23.07 around 17:00 GMT.
“This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new status last week, which should allow him to diversify his activities but pass it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street’s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented Monday also show that the deal has been modified over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares in Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago, Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, told Tokyo, "we thought the participation would be entirely made up of ordinary shares.
But given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert in one year half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares if the latter exchange more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at approximately $47, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that MUFG’s capital will allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, declined to provide details on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to show a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had "clearly" eased his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been arduous for the group, which saw its stock exchange rate melt by half as the cost of insurance against a default risk on its debt flew.
This cost was high on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivor" of Wall Street's major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced that it had raised $15 billion, in part from Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, was the third to vote on a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results of 80% of the suffrage.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a countdown from a non-governmental organization announced a broad “yes” victory, ranging from 63 percent to 70 percent.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
The “Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the seat of the Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was held calmly according to the observer mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, by reserving to it the "development planning" of a country living essentially on oil extraction by foreign companies and currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will serve a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for the ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
