Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by nationalizing it in part. The three countries support, with an interest of 11.2 billion euros in financial aid and a financial contribution of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this matter, also by appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition manager.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been intensifying for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (49%) of the bank’s capital in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell some of its shares, among which, first of all, the activities, essentially insurance, it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
In the second half of the week, serious signs of a crisis have already been revealed at the bank, which is why the Fortis stock has fallen sharply.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to be let go to bankruptcy.
Only on Friday, the company’s shares fell 12 percent, reaching its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, shares have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company’s executives, is not realistic.
The management of the company accuses the uncertainty of the overseas Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout plan, of being at the origin of the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the fund.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's clientele circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also purchased leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market is becoming uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information regarding the prescription of drugs, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s up to you to entrust your chicken to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the program’s creator used to manage medication prescriptions, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage, the health status of the client who is present, and if they feel that the risk is too high, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after learning about the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is easily provided to pharmacies, data on the person's drug purchases over the past eighteen months. From this, the program itself determines what health is and what health the person is suffering from.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk factor, so there is little left to do to the insurer other than paperwork. However, minor problems may still arise.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for various purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat stroke, but they can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others, no.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must ask for permission from the patient before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been treating laboratory analysis results and linking them with data on drug use, so they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of the patient’s health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control over usage is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on expanding the control circle of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the person concerned.
This is another question of whether the person concerned is truly free to give his or her consent, since if he or she refuses, insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus and ultimately, chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are multiplying their trade by two.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, problems.
Today, there will also be a France-India summit where it will be mainly a matter of cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power to which a broader right of expression in international affairs should be given, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not pay much attention to this issue yesterday at the 9th summit in Marseille.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Prime Minister of India, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in a thousand years, they would multiply by two cents, which means the exchange of two cents.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the trade in goods increased from $25 billion to $55 billion, this does not appear to be an over-ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have harmonized from a legal point of view the 26 bilateral agreements with India concerning civil flights, which will also allow air exchanges to take their course in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, which is the EU's first trading partner, on the one hand, and New Delhi, on the other, which ranks only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on this issue has been mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle was also requested, although both have a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains loyal to the energy and climate programme, in particular that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic substances by at least 20 per cent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the fact that it would be necessary to pass a global market at next year’s climate conference, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is heading to the French capital today, where at a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20 billion for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the press agency, the agreement would last for 15 years.
